revision.text:
{{Criminal law}} '''Assaulting, kidnapping, and assassinating the government officials of the United States''', their families, and foreign dignitaries and official guests, is a crime under various statutes, including {{usc|18|111}} ([[Assaulting, resisting, or impeding certain officers or employees]]), {{usc|18|112}} (Protection of foreign officials, official guests, and internationally protected persons), {{usc|18|115}} (Influencing, impeding, or retaliating against a Federal official by threatening or injuring a family member), {{usc|18|351}} ([[U.S. Congress|Congressional]], [[U.S. Cabinet|Cabinet]], and [[U.S. Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] assassination, kidnapping, and assault), and {{usc|18|1751}} ([[U.S. President|Presidential]] and Presidential staff assassination, kidnapping, and assault). Senator [[Robert Byrd]] stated, in introducing the bill that became 18 U.S.C. 351, "This legislation is needed to protect representative democracy. Passage would help guarantee the right of any Member of Congress to fulfill his constitutional duties and responsibilities as an elected official of our country."<ref name=Layton>{{cite court|litigants=United States v. Layton|vol=509|reporter=F. Supp.|opinion=212|court=Dist. Court, ND California|date=1981}}</ref> Until 1982, the legislation was silent as to the court's reach, but now it has been clarified that the court has [[extraterritorial jurisdiction]] over these offenses.<ref>{{citation|url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/hasint6&section=31|volume=6|publisher=Hastings Int'l & Comp. L. Rev.|pages=773|date=1982–1983|title=Extraterritorial Effect of Federal Criminal Statutes: Offenses Directed at Members of Congress, The|author=Petersen, Mark}}</ref>
[[Assault|Minor assault]] or [[Assault|simple assault]] is usually punished as a [[misdemeanor]] with a base [[offense level]] of 4.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a2_3.htm |title=§2A2.3. Minor Assault |publisher=U.S. Sentencing Guidelines |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618200859/http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a2_3.htm |archivedate=2010-06-18 }}</ref> When physical contact occurs or a [[deadly weapon]] is possessed and threatened, it typically escalates to a [[felony]] with a higher offense level, and when injury occurs, the penalties increase still further. When there was intent to commit [[murder]], still higher penalties apply.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a2_1.htm |title=§2A2.1. Assault with Intent to Commit Murder; Attempted Murder |publisher=U.S. Sentencing Guidelines |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619162726/http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a2_1.htm |archivedate=2010-06-19 }}</ref> [[Life imprisonment]] or the [[death penalty]] applies in cases of successful murder.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a1_1.htm |title=§2A1.1. First Degree Murder |publisher=U.S. Sentencing Guidelines |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618234036/http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a1_1.htm |archivedate=2010-06-18 }}</ref> Major penalties apply to [[kidnapping]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a4_1.htm |title=§2A4.1. Kidnapping, Abduction, Unlawful Restraint |publisher=U.S. Sentencing Guidelines |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619112229/http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a4_1.htm |archivedate=2010-06-19 }}</ref>
